A data structure is a specific way of organizing and storing data in a
 computer so that it can be accessed and used efficiently.

A linear data structure is a way of organizing data elements in a sequential 
manner, where each element is connected to a single predecessor and successor
 (except for the first and last elements). This arrangement allows for
  straightforward, single-pass traversal of all elements. 


Non-linear data structures organize data hierarchically or in networks
 rather than sequentially, allowing for efficient, multi-level modeling of 
 complex relationships. Unlike linear structures (arrays, lists), they store
  elements in non-sequential memory, often using pointers to represent relationships,
   with key examples being trees and graphs




   Common Data Structures and Their Uses
Data Structure 	Description	Common Uses
Array	A collection of elements of the same type stored in contiguous memory locations, accessed by an integer index.	Storing a fixed number of items, sorting data, and as a foundation for other data structures.

Linked List	A sequence of nodes, where each node contains data and a reference (link) to the next node.	Implementing browser history, media player playlists, and "undo" operations due to efficient insertions/deletions.

Stack	A linear structure that follows the Last-In, First-Out (LIFO) principle.	Tracking recent actions for "undo" functions, managing function calls in program execution, and parsing expressions.

Queue	A linear structure that follows the First-In, First-Out (FIFO) principle.	Managing shared printer access, scheduling tasks in an operating system, and handling calls in a call center.

Hash Table	Stores data as key-value pairs using a hash function for fast retrieval.	Database indexing, caching, and implementing dictionaries/associative arrays.

Tree	A hierarchical structure with a single parent node (root) branching to child nodes.	Representing file systems, organizational maps, database indexing (B-trees), and decision trees.

Graph	A collection of nodes (vertices) connected by edges representing relationships.	Modeling social networks, transportation systems (GPS routing), and computer networks.
